Small renal mass management in the elderly and the calibration of risk.

Tomaszewski JJ(1), Kutikov A(2).

Author information:
(1)Department of Surgery, MD Anderson Cancer Center at Cooper, Rowan University 
School of Medicine, Camden, NJ.
(2)Division of Urologic Oncology, Fox Chase Cancer Center-Temple University 
Health System, Philadelphia, PA. Electronic address: alexander.kutikov@fccc.edu.

Due to the increased utilization of cross-sectional imaging and prolonged life 
expectancy, the incidence of incidentally diagnosed renal tumors continues to 
rise. While partial nephrectomy is currently recommended as the gold standard 
treatment of cT1a small renal mass whenever technically feasible, the perceived 
benefits of partial nephrectomy may not be applicable to all patient groups. 
Selecting between treatment options in elderly and the infirm can present a 
