Isotopic analysis of island House Martins Delichon urbica indicates marine 
provenance of nutrients.

Cross AD(1), Hentati-Sundberg J(2), Österblom H(2), McGill RA(3), Furness RW(1).

Author information:
(1)College of Medical, Veterinary and Life Sciences, University of Glasgow 
Glasgow, UK.
(2)Stockholm Resilience Centre, Stockholm University Stockholm, Sweden.
(3)Scottish Universities Environmental Research Centre East Kilbride, UK.

The presence of one of the largest colonies of House Martins in Europe on the 
small island of Stora Karlsö, Sweden, led us to investigate the source of their 
food by analysis of stable isotopes of carbon and nitrogen. Carbon isotopic 
values of House Martin nestlings were the same as those of Common Guillemot Uria 
aalge nestlings fed on marine fish, but differed from local Collared Flycatcher 
Ficedula albicollis nestlings fed on woodland insects. We infer that these House 
Martins fed their chicks almost exclusively on insects that had used nutrients 
derived from seabirds, indicating a dependence on the presence of a large 
seabird colony. We suggest by extension that some populations of island 
passerines of high conservation importance may also be dependent on nutrient 
subsidies from seabird colonies.

